 "notes": [
  "The chart is dynamic: add your relevant attribute (INT/WIS/Thaumaturgy/Enlightenment/etc., whichever governs your casting) to the base value shown to get your actual Spell Target.",
  "Roll UNDER (or equal to, per 'match or beat' general dice rule) the Spell Target on 2d10 (01-100) for the spell to succeed.",
  "A natural roll of 96-00 always fails, regardless of the computed Spell Target -- effectively a 95 cap on what you need to roll under. Source docx states explicitly (Damage and Healing by Spellcasting, Martinuk example): 'You always fail a spell on rolls of 96-00.'",
  "Verbatim source image note: 'The spell target does not include your opponent's spell defense modifier.' (Spell/Psychic Defense is applied as a separate modifier per the Basic Spellcasting steps.)",
  "Verbatim source image note: 'The color coding is present to assist you with understanding how difficult a spell cast might be. Green = Easiest, Red = Hardest'",
  "Verbatim source image example: 'If you are using this as a form, you'll need to add your attribute to the target. Ex: a LvL 1 Character attempting to cast at a LvL 2 enemy has a spell target of 40. If that character had an attribute score of 15, the new target would be 55.'",
  "Verbatim source image example: 'If you attempt to target a foe who's spell target is colored red, you do not add your attribute to the target. Ex: In the example above, if the same caster attempted to cast at a level 3, their spell target would be 30, with no modifier.'",
  "Verbatim source image note: 'The fragility of the mortal attempting to manipulate the weave always leaves some room for mistakes. The highest your target can be is 95%.'",
  "Derivation assumption: base value is a function of (target's level - your level) only -- confirmed by cross-referencing every visible cell in both source images; the docx's displayed_at_stat_15 grid equals min(base + 15, 95) for all 400 cells without exception.",
  "RULING (Ed, 2026-07-09): red-zone cells do NOT receive the attribute bonus — Spell Target = raw base value in red; min(base + attribute, 95) elsewhere. The displayed_at_stat_15 grid is the superseded 'always add' render, kept for provenance only. Resolved — see FIDELITY-NOTES §1.2."
 ]
}